## Hard rules — do NOT do any of these

- **Don't commit anything.** Create files, print the checklist, let the user review and commit.
- **Don't run `gh secret set` yourself.** The values come from the admin; print the commands.
- **Don't modify existing files** other than the scaffolded ones. Hands off `package.json`, build configs, source code.
- **Don't run `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`** as part of setup.
- **Don't proceed with an unvalidated baseline SHA.** A non-existent SHA produces silent 100%-template numbers.
- **Don't leave half-written files** if the user cancels mid-flow. Clean up anything written so far.

## Failure modes to handle

- **Not a git repo**: tell the user this command only works inside a git repo, stop.
- **No commits yet**: tell the user to make at least one commit first, stop.
- **User cancels mid-flow**: clean up anything written so far.

## After setup — what the user should expect

**AI Attribution:**
- Every time Claude Code or Cursor writes a file, a snapshot is saved to `.claude/ai_snapshots/` or `.cursor/ai_snapshots/`
- On `git commit`, the message is stamped with a breakdown: `AI: 72% | Human: 28%` per file
- The git hook installs itself the first time an AI session ends after writing files

**Template Metrics:**
- First workflow run produces metrics visible in the Action's artifacts
- DevLake stores a row; Grafana's `$repo` dropdown auto-populates within seconds of the first POST
- Subsequent commits add data points to the time-series panel
